## Breaking Changes (Microsoft.OpenApi v2.0 / OpenAPI 3.1)

The `Microsoft.AspNetCore.OpenApi` 10.0 package upgrades the underlying **Microsoft.OpenApi** library from v1.x to **v2.0**, which targets OpenAPI 3.1 + JSON Schema 2020-12. Here are the issues in your code and fixes:

### 1. `OpenApiAny` types removed → use `JsonNode`

`OpenApiString`, `OpenApiInteger`, `OpenApiObject`, etc. are all gone. Use `System.Text.Json.Nodes` instead.

```csharp
// Before (.NET 9)
using Microsoft.OpenApi.Any;
param.Schema.Example = new OpenApiString("1.0");

// After (.NET 10)
using System.Text.Json.Nodes;
param.Schema.Example = JsonValue.Create("1.0");
```

### 2. `schema.Nullable` property removed

OpenAPI 3.1 uses JSON Schema's `type` arrays instead of a separate `nullable` flag. Check/set nullability via the `Type` flags enum:

```csharp
// Before (.NET 9)
property.Value.Nullable = false;

// After (.NET 10)
// To remove nullability:
if (property.Value.Type.HasFlag(JsonSchemaType.Null))
{
    property.Value.Type &= ~JsonSchemaType.Null;
}
```

(`JsonSchemaType` is a `[Flags]` enum in `Microsoft.OpenApi.Models`.)

### 3. `OpenApiSecurityScheme` / `OpenApiSecurityRequirement`

In OpenApi v2.0, entities are now typed as **interfaces** (`IOpenApiSchema`, etc.) and the `OpenApiSecurityRequirement` is no longer a `Dictionary<OpenApiSecurityScheme, IList<string>>` subclass. Use `OpenApiSecuritySchemeReference` for references:

```csharp
// Before (.NET 9)
var oAuthScheme = new OpenApiSecurityScheme
{
    Reference = new OpenApiReference { Type = ReferenceType.SecurityScheme, Id = "oauth2" }
};
operation.Security = new List<OpenApiSecurityRequirement>
{
    new() { [oAuthScheme] = scopes }
};

// After (.NET 10)
var oAuthScheme = new OpenApiSecuritySchemeReference("oauth2");
operation.Security = new List<OpenApiSecurityRequirement>
{
    new()
    {
        Schemes = new Dictionary<OpenApiSecuritySchemeReference, IList<string>>
        {
            [oAuthScheme] = scopes
        }
    }
};
```

### 4. `OpenApiResponse` → unchanged API, but may need `OpenApiResponseReference`

If you're just adding inline responses, the existing code still works:

```csharp
operation.Responses.TryAdd("401", new OpenApiResponse { Description = "Unauthorized" });
```

---

## Full corrected code

```csharp
using System.Text.Json.Nodes;
using Microsoft.OpenApi.Models;

options.AddOperationTransformer((operation, context, ct) =>
{
    var param = operation.Parameters.FirstOrDefault(p => p.Name == "api-version");
    if (param is not null)
    {
        param.Schema.Example = JsonValue.Create("1.0");
    }

    operation.Responses.TryAdd("401", new OpenApiResponse { Description = "Unauthorized" });

    var oAuthScheme = new OpenApiSecuritySchemeReference("oauth2");
    operation.Security = new List<OpenApiSecurityRequirement>
    {
        new()
        {
            Schemes = new Dictionary<OpenApiSecuritySchemeReference, IList<string>>
            {
                [oAuthScheme] = scopes
            }
        }
    };

    return Task.CompletedTask;
});

options.AddSchemaTransformer((schema, context, ct) =>
{
    if (schema.Properties is not null)
    {
        foreach (var property in schema.Properties)
        {
            if (schema.Required?.Contains(property.Key) != true)
            {
                // Remove Null from the type flags to make non-required fields non-nullable
                if (property.Value.Type.HasFlag(JsonSchemaType.Null))
                {
                    property.Value.Type &= ~JsonSchemaType.Null;
                }
            }
        }
    }
    return Task.CompletedTask;
});
```

